=0A[7] That=E2=80=99s approximate; Vanguard also had some state settlements=
 and there is =0Asome double-counting. The SEC says: =E2=80=9CVanguard agre=
ed to be censured, cease and =0Adesist from future violations, and pay $18.=
2 million in disgorgement and =0Aprejudgment interest that will be deemed s=
atisfied by the payment of $92.91 =0Amillion in relief ordered by the state=
s=E2=80=99 settlements and a $13.5 million civil =0Apenalty, for a total am=
ount of $106.41 million to be distributed to affected =0Ainvestors through =
a Fair Fund. The $106.41 million in ordered relief is in =0Aaddition to $40=
 million that Vanguard agreed to pay to settle an investor class =0Aaction.=
=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[8] A target date fund is a retirement fund with a particula=
r target date: If =0Ayou plan to retire around 2045, you buy a 2045 target =
fund, and that fund has =0Asome asset allocation that generally starts aggr=
essive and becomes more =0Aconservative as you approach (and then pass) the=
 target date. Generally these =0Afunds do their allocation by investing in =
some mix of other Vanguard funds. =0AVanguard=E2=80=99s funds covered in th=
is order run from 2015 to 2065, in five-year =0Aincrements.=0A=0A[9] Actual=
ly many separate funds, one for each retirement vintage, but for =0Aeach vi=
ntage =E2=80=94 say, =E2=80=9Cretire in 2030=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 there was a=
n Investor fund and a =0Aseparate Institutional fund.=0A=0A[10] There are m=
utual fund rules <> about how they are allowed to do this, but =0Athat=E2=
=80=99s not the point.=0A=0A[11] It=E2=80=99s actually quite important that=
 this happened in late 2020. Basically =0Awhat happened is that Vanguard=E2=
=80=99s working group started thinking about this in =0Aearly 2020, when st=
ock prices had collapsed due to Covid, so they figured =E2=80=9Cehh =0Ano o=
ne has any capital gains anyway.=E2=80=9D TheSEC says <>: =E2=80=9CThe Work=
ing Group =0Aobserved that, through early 2020, accumulated realized capita=
l gains in the =0AInvestor TRFs averaged 0.5%, consistent with historical n=
umbers. However, this =0Aobservation was based on evaluations of capital ga=
ins during a one-month period =0Abetween late February and March 2020. Beca=
use the financial markets had =0Adeclined substantially at the time due to =
consequences from the COVID-19 =0Apandemic, the Working Group assumed that =
capital gains would continue to be =0Amodest for Investor TRFs in the fores=
eeable future.=E2=80=9D But by the time the plans =0Awere finalized later i=
n the year, stocks had recovered and there were a lot =0Amore taxable gains=
