. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Forecasts contribute to the optimal bottom line in a comp=
licated, nonlinear way, and the sum of the contributions, however computed,=
 does not normally add up to the total.=C2=A0</p> </blockquote> <p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Isichenko is discussing the most important question in qu=
antitative finance: =E2=80=9CHow much is my bonus=3F=E2=80=9D Generally spe=
aking, the more value a researcher adds to the overall trading model, the m=
ore she gets paid. The way you add value to the overall trading model, crud=
ely speaking, is (1) the model trades on your signals and (2) the stocks th=
at it buys on your signals go up.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you a=
re a quantitative researcher, you could imagine gaming this. One form of ga=
ming is:=C2=A0</p> <ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40p=
x; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You find a signal. I=
t=E2=80=99s pretty good, not amazing, but pretty good.</li> <li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">You hand it off to your boss and it goes into the big tr=
ading model.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The big trading model d=
oesn=E2=80=99t make much use of it, because it is too correlated with other=
 signals.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore, you do not get =
paid very much for the signal you found.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">You find those other signals and break their kneecaps.</li> <li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now the big trading model stops using the other si=
gnals and uses yours instead.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Yours =
is pretty good, so it makes money, so you get paid.</li> </ol> <p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">The problem with this is that you can=E2=80=99t really bre=
ak the kneecaps of statistical models of stock price returns. What you=C2=
=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>do, maybe, is trick the big trading model into think=
ing that your signal is uncorrelated with the other signals. Then the big t=
rading model will use your signal a lot =E2=80=94=C2=A0it will trade a lot =
of stock based on your signal =E2=80=94=C2=A0because uncorrelated signals a=
re very useful. And you will get paid a lot.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Is this bad=3F Well, sure, I mean, the big trading model was optimized t=
o achieve high risk-adjusted returns, and by tricking it into using more of=
 your signal, you break that optimization. The model will achieve lower ris=
k-adjusted returns. But maybe higher absolute returns; who knows=3F By brea=
king the model in this way, you cause it to double down on your signal, to =
put more money into your signal than it deserves. If your signal works pret=
ty well, then for a while this could actually be=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>fo=
r the model=E2=80=99s performance; it is taking more risk but possibly earn=
ing higher returns.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway this is not any=
 sort of advice about anything, and in general if you are a researcher at a=
 quant firm, tricking your firm=E2=80=99s trading models in this way is (1)=
